{
  "message": "perf(og): set long-lived immutable cache-control on every OpenGraph / Twitter image route\n\nEvery route-level `ImageResponse` in `app/**/{opengraph,twitter}-image.tsx`\nand the shared article helper in `lib/article-social-image.tsx` now\nreturns:\n\n    cache-control: public, immutable, no-transform, max-age=31536000\n\nWhy this matters:\n\n- These endpoints are hit by link-preview crawlers (Twitter/X,\n  Slack/Discord, LinkedIn, iMessage, Mastodon/Bluesky, Facebook,\n  Telegram). Without an explicit cache header they fall back to\n  Next.js's default, which for dynamic ImageResponse routes is very\n  short \u2014 crawlers fetch the 1200x630 PNG over and over on every\n  share of a URL.\n- The rendered PNGs are a pure function of the route + page data that\n  lives in the component source. Any real content change ships via a\n  new deploy, which already busts the immutable URL (Next emits a new\n  deployment URL), so `immutable` + 1 year is safe.\n- `no-transform` blocks Cloudflare / ISP image rewrite, which mangles\n  fonts (next/og renders SVG \u2192 PNG and image-transform proxies break\n  the glyph outlines).\n\nTouches only the `headers` field inside the existing `ImageResponse`\nconstructor call \u2014 no layout, size, font, or rendering change.\n\nAll of these routes share the same pattern: they build the PNG\nvia next/og and return it. The only routes NOT touched here are\nthe ones whose hero illustration had to change (separate commit);\nthis commit is purely a cache-layer change.",
